{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957112701/1029.xml":{"full_text":"W\\* Spawns J&faf\nWith Sunday Morning edition\nPublished by\nTHI EVENING STAR NEWSPAPER COMPANY\nWASHINGTON 4, 0. C.\nSamuel H. KauHmann\nPresident\nBenjamin M. McKelwoy\ntditer\nMAIN OPFICt. nth M. and Penntylyanki A\u00bbe. (4)\nNSW YORK: 342 Modi ton Avo (12)\nCHICAGO! 221 N U Soil* 31 (I)\nDETROITi Now Contor Building (2)\nSAN ERANCISCO: Rum Building (4)\nLOS ANGELESi 3242 Wott Bth St. (5)\nEUROPEAN BUREAU\u2014\nPARIS, PRANCE, 21 Ruo Do Bottl\nDelivered by Carrier\nPruning and Sunday Sunday Evonlng\nMantMy 1.95 Pot Imuo JO Monthly 1.30\nWookly AS Wookly 30\nNight Final and Sunday 2.00 Night Nnal 0n1y...!A0\nRatg* by Mail\u2014Payobl* in Adranct\nAnywhoro In th* UnHod Stator\nPruning and Sunday Sunday Evonlng\n1 year 28 00 1 yoar ...12.00 1 yoar 18 00\n4 month* 14.30 4 month* 6.30 6 montht 923\n3 months 7JO 3 months 3.30 3 months 4.73\n1 month 2.60 I month IJO 1 month 2.00\nTolophonoi STsrllng 3-3000\nlotorad at tho Pott Office. Washington. D. C\nos second clast mall matter\nMember of tha Associated Press\nTim Associated Press ft entitled exclusively to the use for\nrepublication of all the local nows printed In this newspaper\nwell as A. P newt dispatches\nA-12\nWEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 27, 1957\n\nStricken President\nThe encouraging aspect of the Pres\nident\u2019s latest Illness\u2014the third serious\nattack he has had in a little more than\ntwo years\u2014lies In the hope expressed by\nhis doctors for \u201ccomplete recovery within\na reasonable period of time.\u201d\nThey did not spell out what they\nmeant by a reasonable period of time.\nThe medical report did say, however,\nthat the President will require \u201ca period\nof rest and substantially decreased ac\ntivity estimated at several weeks.\u201d We\nhope this means that the President will\nhave made a \u201ccomplete recovery\u201d within\nseveral weeks. But the doctors did not\nquite say this, and it may be that Mr.\nEisenhower will be away from his desk\nfor an appreciably longer period. It Is not\nthe time required for Mr. Eisenhower\u2019s\nrecovery, however, which will concern\nthe American people and which should\nconcern the President. Thp important\nthing is that he get well\u2014no matter how\nlong it takes.\nMeanwhile, of course, the affairs of\nstate must move ahead. The task of be\nstirring ourselves to meet the Russian\nchallenge In missiles and related fields\ncannot wait. The job of preparing a\nbudget and a legislative program for a\nCongress which returns In January must\ngo forward. Someone will have to substi\ntute for the President at the meeting of\nthe NATO Council In Paris next month.\nAnd there are other hardly less impor\ntant matters clamoring for attention.\nThere has been a suggestion that Mr.\nEisenhower, if he cannot attend to these\nthings himself, can at least make the\nImportant decisions. We doubt very\nmuch that this is correct. A man as sick'\nas he Is cannot properly deal with such\nthings, and the President should not be\nburdened with them. It may be, as the\nmedical report says, that the plugged\nblood vessel In the President\u2019s brain is\na \u201csmall\u201d branch of the middle cerebral\nartery on the left side. But even this Is\na serious matter, and the doctors con\ncede as much when they say that Mr.\nElsenhower\u2019s \u201cpresent condition is mild\nand is expected to be transitory In na\nture.\u201d He should not be called upon to\ndo anything which might adversely af\nfect his present condition or disappoint\nthe expectation of his doctors. In short,\nthe President must devote himself to rest\nand recuperation.\nIt is up to the Eisenhower \u201cteam\u201d to\ntake over. They will be handicapped by\nthe President\u2019s disability. But they have\nassumed much responsibility in the past,\nand they can do it again. We hope that\nthe team members will step into the\nbreach and that they will have the sup\nport, especially during this critical pe\nriod, of all Americans of whatever\npolitical faith. If this support is forth\ncoming we suspect that knowledge of it\nwill do as much as anything else to speed\nthe President\u2019s recovery.\na\n'As New Jersey Goes\u2014 7\nThere is little doubt now that New\nJersey will provide one of the most in\nteresting and significant political tests\nof 1958. And in the outcome will be\nfound some tangible clues as to what\nmight fairly be expected on the Nation\nwide stage in 1960.\nThe latest development in New\nJersey\u2019s emergence as a critical battle\nground next year came with announce\nment by Senator H. Alexander Smith, a\nthree-time Republican winner, that he\nwill not stand for re-election. Earlier\nthis month, Bernard M. Shanley, former\nspecial counsel and appointment secre\ntary at the White House, announced his\nown candidacy for the Q. O. P. senatorial\nnomination. Mr. Shanley has some en\nergetic party supporters in the so-called\nGarden State, but there has been ample\nevidence that he is not the early favor\nite of the organization leadership. Sev\neral other New Jersey Republicans, in\ncluding at least two of the State\u2019s Con\ngressmen, have expressed active interest\nin the senatorial nomination and the\nprospects of avoiding a bruising G. O. P.\nprimary fight are not good.\nIn the years when pro-Republlean\nlsm was \"normal\" in Jersey a G. O. P.\nprimary skirmish was only another step\ntoward victory in November. There are\nsigns that times have changed. Although\nthe Eisenhower-Nixon ticket carried the\nSlate both In 1952 and 1956, Democrat\nRobert B. Meyner won the governorship\nin 1953 and again this year. On this\nlast occasion his party won both\nbranches of the State Assembly for. the\nfirst time in 20 years. Mr. Meyner,\nyoung and moderately liberal, has been\nmentioned often as a possible Demo\ncratic presidential lwminee in 1960. He\nIs undoubtedly in position to name the\nparty\u2019s senatorial candidate, with little\nrisk of provoking any serious factional\nfuss. The Democratic chances of win\nning the Senate seat, therefore, seem\nbright. And, if this happens, Mr.\nMeyner\u2019s national prestige will be\nincreased accordingly.\nBlaming the Politicians\ni The Christian Century, a respected\n\u201cundenominational Journal of religion,\u201d\nhas called upon the churches of Vir\nginia\u2019s Prince Edward County to resist\nthe threat to close the public schools\nthere In event of integration. It urges\nthe churches to refuse to permit use of\ntheir facilities for private schools, and\nit has every right, of course, to issue\nsuch an appeal.\nUnfortunately, however, the Chris\ntian Century seems to have little'under\nstanding of the actual situation In Prince\nEdward. It speaks disparagingly of \u201ca\nState political machine made arrogant\nby its recent lopsided victory at the\np 0115...\u201d It says that in Prince Edward\nCounty \u201cpolitical leaders\u201d have formed\na $200,000 private educational corpora\ntion and have called upon churches to\nmake their facilities available to house\nthe proposed new school system. It\nexpresses the hope that \u201cthe churches\nrealize that the whole scheme will col\nlapse if they refuse to give it their\nsanction.\u201d\nThis is comment which reflects\nIgnorance of the facts in Prince Edward\nand which, we believe, tends to do more\nharm than good. The private educa\ntional corporation was set up two years\nago\u2014long before the political machine\nwas made \u201carrogant\u201d by its victory at\nthe polls earlier this month. The cor\nporation was not formed by political\nleaders. It was formed at a mass meet\ning of white citizens and none of its\nofficers is a politician. There are about\n4,500 white adults in Prince Edward.\nThese are the people who have pledged\nthe $200,000, and 90 per cent of them\nhave signed a petition calling upon the\ncounty authorities to close the schools\nif they should be integrated. Among\nthese signers are many of the county\u2019s\nchurch leaders.\nIt is important, in our opinion, that\nthese facts be recognized. It is utterly\nerroneous to assert or to suggest that\nthe move to abandon public schools in\nthe county in event of integration is the\nwork of \u201cpolitical leaders.\u201d For it is\nnothing of the sort. If the schools are\nclosed, this will be done at the demand\nof the overwhelming majority of white\nresidents, most of whom are church\ngoers. It may be argued that this atti\ntude is wrong. Nevertheless, it is a fact.\nThis unyielding public sentiment exists\nand it must be taken into account if\nthere is to be any hope of solving the\nproblem in Prince Edward. The prob\nlem is one which involves a whole com\nmunity, not a few politicians. To create\nany Impression to the contrary merely\nadds to the hopelessness of a situation\nthat is already hopeless enough.\nPoor Performance\nIt is difficult to excuse the way the\nWhite House handled the news of the\nPresident\u2019s latest illness. By midafter\nnoon on Monday, the doctors had found\nMr. Eisenhower suffering not merely\nfrom a \u201cchill,\u201d but also from a mild\naphasia\u2014a speech impairment usually,\nthough not always, associated with an\nactually or potentially serious brain\nJesion. Nevertheless, hours later, the\nAmerican people were given no hint of\nthis. Instead, they were led to believe\u2014\nuntil about three o\u2019clock yesterday\u2014that\nhis condition was not particularly worri\nsome, that he was eating heartily, and\nthat he was progressing \u201cvery well,\u201d or\nat least \u201csatisfactorily.\u201d But now we\nknow otherwise, although happily the\noutlook for his complete recovery, ac\ncording to the doctors, appears to be\n\u201cexcellent.\u201d\nPerhaps one ought not to be critical\nIn a situation of this kind. Yet it seems\nevident that the White House staff per\nformed poorly in this instance. If Jim\nHagerty had been here at the time,\nInstead of in Paris, the story might well\nhave been 'handled with much more\ncandor and dispatch. We do not believe,\nhowever, that Mrs. Anne Wheaton, his\nassociate as press secretary, is to be\nblamed for what happened. On the con\ntrary, we strongly suspect that she gave\nout all the news she was allowed to\nknow by people higher up. They are\nthe seem vulnerable to the\ncharge of bad judgment in needlessly\nwithholding the facts of the President\u2019s\ncondition from the people.\nG\n'Small Change' Machine\nA Chicago inventor, German-bom\nWilliam A. Patzer, has built a machine\nthat will change $1 bills into quarters,\ndimes and nickels. It rejects bills of any\nother denomination, and scorns any\nform of counterfeit paper. Witnesses at\na demonstration have been Impressed,\nand quite logically. Mr. Patzer probably\nis correct in saying that his machine will\nmake possible the selling of a greatly\nIncreased number of items in vending\nmachines, and perhaps that a \u201ccom\npletely automated supermarket\u201d is only\na simple step away.\nIt has become apparent that old\nfashioned shoppers are fighting a losing\nbattle against automation. From ma\nchines that sell chewing gum to ones\nthat sell cigarettes was an easy transi\ntion. Buying potatoes the same way\nmay prove equally acceptable. Indeed, if\nMr. Patzer's machine has a weakness it\nmay be its inflexible requirement that\nit will accept only \u201cthe kind of cur\nrency the average person carries in a\nwallet or purse.\u201d Some of today\u2019s prices\nare threatening to leave very little cur\nrency in the average person\u2019s wallet, or\nat best to require much change for a\ndollar bIU.\nChristen Thee Too Little and Too Late-nikT\nLETTERS TO THE STAR\nPraises President\nA Congressman on five\nmonths\u2019 vacation condemns\nthe President for taking a\nweek end for golf. A gentle\nman who has done nothing\nwhatever for six years but\nrun for President, sneers at\nthe \u201crecumbent in the White\nHouse.\u201d.\nI am getting tired of this\ncontinual sniping at one of\nour great men and I suspect\nthat most Americans agree\nwith me. They have twice in\ndicated their preference for\nhim.\nHe is a man of such abso\nlute Integrity and patriotism\nthat his political enemies can\nfind no point on to\nattack him so they make this\nuntrue point of inactivity.\nWould that all our Presi\ndents had been as active and\nearnest in their endeavors.\nI for one am grateful to him\nfor his life-long unselfish\nservice to our country. I hope\nhe will take all the recreation\nhe feels he needs.\nHis opponents make up in\nnoise what they lack in num\nbers. I wish the pverwhelm\ning majority of his admirers\nhad some way of thanking\nhim. He must occasionally\nfeel the need of encourage\nment. Could we not stage an\nappreciation campaign? Pre\nsent the true picture of the\nPresident at his work. In\nvite people to write \u201cThank\nyou Mr. President\u201d letters for\nChristmas. Let us do this\nnow. It would show our\nforeign friends and foes that\nhis country is with him in\nthese critical times.\nVeritas.\nRebukes Educators\nI have read with interest\nyour paper\u2019s recent report on\nthe controversy concerning\nthe pamphlet about Soviet\neducation issued by the\nUnited States Office of Edu\ncation of the Department of\nHealth. Education and Wel\nfare. Obviously, the contro\nversial facts of the pamphlet\ncould be commented upon\nonly after comparing the two\ndisputed texts and by a per\nson familiar with Soviet edu\ncation and Russian language.\nHowever, two aspects of\nthe controversy, in my opin\nion even more disturbing and\nwhich have been completely\noverlooked in the press and\nradio reports, should be\nbrought to the attention of\nthe American public.\nThe fact that the Office\nof Education had to hire an\nanalyst on a temporary basis\nto survey Soviet education\nseems to indicate that none\nof their permanent stall\nmembers is sufficiently fa\nmiliar with the Soviet and\nEastern European area\n(which of course requires\na thorough knowledge of\nRussian and possibly other\nSlavic languages) to under\ntake such study. This ap\nparent neglect and under\nestimation of Soviet educa\ntional standards is. in view\nof our \u201ctotal competition\u201d\nwith the Soviet Union, ut\nterly incomprehensible and\ndisturbing.\nAnother disquieting fact il\nthat the Office of Education\ntook 14 months to revise a\nreport written by an analyst\nin eight months, which lost\nus at least one year of\nprecious time in an era when\ntime is not money but sur-\nvival Itself.\nIf this deplorable situation\nhas been caused by the as\nsumed lack of qualified\npersonnel in the Office of\nEducation, steps should be\nimmediately taken to remedy\nit.\nNicholas T. Nonnenmacher.\nAdvice\nLet\u2019s have a Nation-wide\ncampaign to prevent the\nspread of cold and flu germs I\n\u2019Epidemics are started by\nthe spread of germs from\nperson to person.\nDon\u2019t wait until you are so\nill you have to go to bed\u2014\nif you have cold or flu symp\ntoms (even without fever)\nstay at home until the symp\ntoms have disappeared or\nyou are well.\nWhat may be \u201conly a cold\u201d\nfor one person may mean\npneumonia or death for an\nother \u2014if we continue to\nspread the germs.\nIsabella Chartres.\nPen names may be used it\nletters carry writers' correct\nnames and addresses AU\nletters are subject to conden\nsation.\n'Law in the News'\nThose lawyer columnists\nYeager and Stark have taken\nleave of their reason in the\narticle \u201cBirth Control by Fiat\nBecoming Top Issue.\u201d\nFirst, they assert that\nthere are only two solutions\nto what they call \u201cthe pop\nulation dilemma.\u201d If there\nis at least one solution, then\nthere is no \u201cdilemma.\u201d Else\nwhat are the hqrns of a\ndilemma?\nSecond, they offer no evi\ndence of the logical legerde\nmain by which they arrived\nat \u201conly two solutions,\u201d and\nhence their gratuitous asser\ntion can be gratuitously re\njected as a manifestly incom\nplete statement of alterna\ntives. Furthermore, their hon\nesty is suspect in listing as\nthe first solution migration\nto the moon\u2014a straw man\nborn of Sputnik; and their\nnaivete is revealed in naming\nbirth control, presumably\nartificial birth control, as the\nother. Birth controller and\neconomist Charles Issawi,\nrecommending contraception\nfor Egypt, sadly admits that\njust as it took 50 years for\nbirth control to have any\neffect upon the British pop\nulation so also will it take\n50 years in Egypt; but by\nthat time (2020 A. D.), ac\ncording to birth controllers\nYeager and Stark, we\u2019ll be\nswamped. So what good is a\nsolution that is no solution?\nThird, they contradict\nthemselves by saying, on the\none hand, that experts are\n\u201cwondering\u201d if legally en\nforced birth control is not\nthe answer, and, on the other,\nthat \u201cthose who have given\nthe subject serious thought\nseem agreed that law is not\nthe answer.\u201d What\u2019s the\nmatter\u2014haven\u2019t the \u201cex\nperts\u201d who have been \u201cwon\ndering\u201d given the subject\n\u201cserious thought\u201d?\nTo compound the confu\nsion, Yeager and Stark admit\nthat \u201cno experts confess\u201d ad\nvocacy of birth control by flat\nand that \u201cthe very thought\nhas been taboo.\u201d Yet some\nhow our columnists have\nmanaged to penetrate their\n\"wondering\u201d and perceive\ntherein a \u201ctop issue.\u201d Inter\nesting.\nThis Yeager-Stark flight\nfrom reason is typical birth\ncontrol irrationality. The\nstrange readiness, nay eager\nness, to admit the bankruptcy\nof human thought\u2014to fasten\nupon the panacea of birth\ncontrol as a substitute for\nthe admittedly hard, honest\nthinking and acting required\nby a complex human problem\n\u2014was unmasked years ago by\nG. K. Chesterton when he\nasked what birth controllers\nwould do in a case where\nthey had ten heads but only\nseven hats. Lop off three\nheads, or make three more\nhats?' Planned parenthood\nadvocates still think it more\nliberal and rational to invert\nthe natural order of ends and\nmeans and lop off three\nheads.\nArlingtonlan.\nSpreading the Word\nIn a recent letter I criti\ncized our propaganda short\ncomings in the field of poli\ntics, and urged that we\nspread abroad an under\nstanding of our system and\nIdeals.\nNow comes the welcome\nnews that George Allen, the\nnew director of the USIA. will\nbe in close relationship with\nthe State Department, the\nNational Security Council,\nand with the President him\nself.\nIt is to be hoped that this\ncrganlzational relationship\nwill be expressed in actual\noperations Such relation\nship and operations will not\nthemselves Insure that we will\nourselves emphasize basic\nprinciples and try to spread\na knowledge and apprecia\ntion of those principles. But\nthe news does give rise to\nhope that we shall not con\ntinue to default entirely In\nthe war.\nLloyd Baehaaa*.\nQur Ground Missiles\nThere has been much\nbreast-beating over our sat\nellite and missile situation.\nBut I wonder how much we\nare willing to give up to catch\nup.\nStepping up our missile\nprogram necessitates men,\nmaterial, ideas and, above\nall, the will. We in the United\nStates have been riding high\n\u2014something like 46 inches\nabove the ground\u2014in fancy\nvehicles called automobiles.\nIn lieu of a high-altitude\nmissile program, we have a\nstupendous on the ground\nprogram in the hands of a\nlarge fraction of our public.\nI suggest that the metals,\nengineering skill, and the\nmanufacturing power that\nnow goes into our ground\nborne missiles, in the form of\nfantastic and superfluous\ngrill-work and headlights, be\nredirected into a missile that\ncould withstand re-entry into\nthe atmosphere from high\naltitudes.\nI also suggest that we re\nmove the costly and unneces\nsary fins and superfluous tail\nlights from'the \u2018automobile.\nOur rockets need the fins\nmuch more and the glare of\nthe present taillight mon\nstrosities would look much\nmore beautiful were we to\nwatch a rocket disappear into\nspace. I do not believe that\nit makes good sense to sacri\nfice an air-borne rocket pro\ngram for a ground-borne\nrocket program. Let\u2019s see if\nthe public is flbiious about its\nwillingness to defend Itself I\nL.S.T.\nTeachers College\nIn a public statement last\nweek, the President of the\nBoard of Education; Walter\nTobriner, proposed the sub\nstitution of a junior college\nfor the present D. C. Teach\ners College.\nOur association views with\ngrave concern any proposal\nwhich would reduce the edu\ncational opportunity of our\nyoung people for higher edu\ncation. It is most dishearten\ning that this proposal comes\nat a time when the United\nStates Office of Education\npredicts that total college en\nrollments will double in the\nnext 13 years\u2014and that a\nshortage of facilities is an\nticipated. We wonder too that\nthis lowering of our sights\ncomes at a time when the\nPresident of the United\nStates reminds us of our Na\ntion\u2019s need for a highly edu\ncated citizenry.\nThis critical lack of future\nhigher educational facilities\nis even more ominous for\nour own children. In every\none of the 48 States higher\neducation is provided all\neligible persona at partial\npublic expense. But here in\nWashington these advantages\nare denied our children\u2014\nwith the exception of re\nstricted teacher education.\nEven States with total popu\nlations of less than half that\nof our city support broad\nand varied programs for\ntheir own youth.\nTherefore, our association\nbelieves that the D. C. Teach\ners College should be ex\npanded into a strong compre\nhensive city college with of\nferings in teacher education\nand the liberal arts and\nsciences.\nHenry Segal,\nExecutive Board, Lamond-\nRlggs Citizens Association.\nLaboratory Animals\nAn experiment conducted\nby doctors at Walter Reed\nused 19 pairs of monkeys to\ndiscover how ulcers are\ncaused, not how ulcers are\ncured.\nIt is the cruel waste of\nrepetitive and proven experi\nments which concecn persons\ninterested in animal welfare.\nThe English anti-cruelty\nlaw has been in force for\n100 years. This regulates\nmedical experimentation, and\noutstanding scientific dis\ncoveries have been made dur\ning that period in their\nlaboratories. Their system of\nlicenses and controls which\nlimit both* needless cruelty\nand waste of animals shows\nthem to be more civilised\nand humane than we are in\nthis country.\nB.T. West.\n\u2022v\nVISTAS IN SCIENCE\n>By THOMAS ft. HENRY\nThanksgiving Has a Foreign Flavor\nHie world, the ages and a\nhalf doaen vanished civilisa\ntions make their contribu\ntions to the American\nThanksgiving dinner.\nPumpkins, squash, beans\nand potatoes from America,\nonions from ancient Egypt,\npeas from Ethiopia, parsnips\nand turnips from ancient\nChina\u2014\nAztec, Maya, the skin\nwrapped Cro-Magnon all did\ntheir part In the darkness of\npre-history to make possible\nthe plates which are loaded\nso lavishly. They did better\nthan they knew. Very few\nnew vegetables have been\nintroduced in historic times.\nIn many cases little improve\nment has been made on the\nproducts of the ancients.\nThe story of potatoes alofie\ncontains enough romance and\nadventure for a fair-sized\nnovel. This vegetable was one\nof America's greatest con\ntributions to civilization. Its\norigin is unknown, out its\nwanderings from America to\nEurope and back to America\nagain constitute a fascinating\nstory.\nDie species of cultivated\nlettuce never has been found\nwild. It is believed to have\nbeen derived from India or\nCentral Asia. It is one of the\noldest known vegetables. Her\nodotus, Hippocrates and Aris\ntotle mention it in Greek\ngardens. Chaucer refers to its\ncultivation in England in\n1340. It was brought to Amer\nica very early and 16 varieties\nare listed as being grown in\nAmerican gardens in 1806.\nCelery Long Avoided\nCelery is a biennial plant\nnative to the marshlands of\nsouthern Europe, North\nAfrica and southwestern Asia.\nIt long was considered poison\nous and was not used as food\nuntil modem times.\nThe Israelites complained\nto Moses in the wilderness\nbecause they couldn\u2019t have\nonions to which they had be\ncome accustomed during the\ncaptivity in Egypt. The cul\ntivated onion, according to a\nDepartment of Agriculture\nreport, probably originated in\nAfghanistan. There is no\nrecord of its introduction to\nNorth America.\nPumpkins and squashes\nwere grown in America long\nbefore white men came on\nthe scene. Remains of both\nhave been found among ruins\nTHIS AND THAT\nBy CHARLES E. TRACEWELL\n\u201cALEXANDRIA, Va.\n\u201cDear Sir;\n\u201cWe had a happy little\ncat come to our house re\ncently.\n\u201cHe has one blue eye and\none yellow eye. Oil. yes, I\nforgot to say it is a White cat.\n\u201cHe is a Persian, and such\na tail nobody ever saw. We\ncall him Fluffy, not a very\noriginal name, I guess, but it\nfits.\n\u201cNaming animals is a\ngame of mine. I love to try\nto make the name selected\nreally mean something.\n\u201cThere are too many\nBlackie and Whitle sort of\nnames. Maybe you think\nFluffy is not very original,\neither, but if you could see\nhim, you would be sure it\nis a good name.\n\u201cDo the Persians take any\nspecial care, or feeding?\n\u201cYours truly, G.G.R.\u201d\n\nThe oddity of different col\nored eyes is a white Persian\ncat trait.\nThese woolly creatures\nneed special care in handling,\nthat is, they demand combing\nat all times.\nStone people do not like to\nown them on this account.\nThe long hair tends to get\nmatted, and to make knots,\nespecially on the under sides,\nand on the legs.\nThe woolly character of\nthis type of cat sets it apart\nfrom the common short\nhairs, as they are called.\nIn habits, they are much\nlike the common ones, and'\nare not sissies, by any means.\nWe knew a fine one called\nSmoky, a gray, naturally\nenough, who foraged for rats\nand brought many of them\nhome.\nYet Smoky was as fine\nand gentle a cat with humans\nas you could find.\nHe also had that trait,\nsometimes found in people,\nof mixing with others with\nout raising any resentment\nwhatever.\nWe imagine this is a Per\nsian cat trait.\nAs a stranger, such a wan\nderer is able to move into a\nnew home without upsetting\nother cats which may be\nthere.\nThey do not resent him,\nand he does not resent them.\n4\nAnother thing to be\nwatched in the Persians is\near mites.\nThese pests of all cats seem\nQUESTIONS AND ANSWERS\nBy THE HASKIN SERVICE\nA reader ran let an answei or mall to any factual queetlon or wntlnc\nThe Evening Star.lnformation Bureau. 1200 Bye (treat MW. Washington t.\nD C Please inclose 3 cents for return ooatage\nQ. Do many people take itecture. as well as academic\ncorrespondence courses in studies in general.\ntechnical subjects?\u2014N. B.\nA. About 700,000 persons\nenroll in correspondence\ncourses each year, according\nto the National Home Study\nCouncil, and the courses in\nradio, television and elec\ntronics are now attracting\nmore students than are any\nother courses. Next in popu\nlarity are courses in religion\nand mechanical trades. Many\nstudents also enroll for such\nsubjects as buslnsm. real\nestate, engineering and areft-\nof settlements of the Basket\nMakers, about the earliest\nagricultural people on this\ncontinent. Probably both\ncame from Mexico. The Hub\nbard squash came to light in\nMarblehead. Mass., In 1855.\nIt had been growing there\nfor more than 50 years.\nAnother popular winter\nsquash came from seeds fur\nnished by the Iroquois In\ndians.\nPeas are the oldest known\nvegetables. They are believed\nto have originated in Ethi\nopia but to have spread over\nEurope and Asia long before\nthe dawn of history. They\nwere eaten\u2014perhaps even\ncultivated after a fashion\u2014\nby men of the New Stone\nAge in Europe. Columbus\nplanted some in the West\nIndies in 1493. They spread\nrapidly among the Indians.\nThey constituted one of the\nchief crops of the Iroquois\nwhich were destroyed by\nGen. Sullivan in the cam\npaign of 1779.\nThe species from which\ncabbage is derived grows wild\nin North Africa and along\nthe European shore of the\nMediterranean, it has been\ncultivated for 4,000 years.\nGreeks and Romans grew it\nin their gardens. Most of the\nAmerican varieties origi\nnated in the gardens of\nNorth Europe.\nTurnips From China\nThe turnip is a native of\noentral and western China.\nSeed probably was brought\nto America by some of the\nearliest European settlers.\nThe radish is a native of\nChina and India. It was cul\ntivated by both the Greeks\nand tfie Egyptians.\nThe parsnip is another\nAsiatic root crop which first\nwas planted in Virginia in\n1609 and in Massachusetts\nin 1629. Only recently has it\ngotten away from the home\ngarden to become a commer\ncial crop.\nPopcorn is peculiarly\nAmerican. In early Spanish\nwritings references made to\na ritual of the Aztecs in\nwhich \u201cone hour before dawn\nthere sallied forth all these\nmaidens crowned with gar\nlands of maize, toasted and\npopped, the grains of which\nwere like orange blossoms\u2014\nand on their necks thick fes\ntoons of the same which\npassed under the left arm.\u201d\nto rather specialize in irri\ntating the Persian\u2019s ears.\nThere seem to be more\nconvolutions in and around\ntheir ears than in and around\nthe ears of the shorthalrtd\nones. Just what these\n\u201cpockets\u201d alongside the cat\nears are for nobody seems to\nknow, but they make excel\nlent hiding places for the\nmites.\nEar mites are not trans\nferrable to people, so no one\nneed worry about catching\nanything. The poor cat, how\never, is made miserable, and\nif the condition is allowed to\ngo unchecked, it may necessi\ntate the removal of part of\nthe infected ear.\nSo the best thing to do,\nwhen a cat digs at its ear, is\nto take it to a good veterina\nrian. The cat does not need\nhospitalization, and two\ntreatments usually will end\nthe trouble.\nHome medication is not ad\nvised. because the amateur\ncannot tell when the mites\nare destroyed.\n\nCat owners might be in\nterested to know that au\nthorities. of which America\nhas so many, say that there\nare 24 diseases which may be\ncaught from dogs, and only\n12 which may be caught from\ncats.\nWith ordinary care, noth\ning whatever need be\u2019eaught\nfrom dog or cat.\nIf this were not true, these\nanimals would not be the\nuniversal favorites they are,\nbecause there are enough\nways to \"catch something\u201d\nwithout introducing disease\nbearers.\nThe maladies of dogs and\ncats are their own, and sel\ndom invade the human\nsystem.\nEven their tricky disease,\ndistemper, so much like our\nown Influenza, never \u201cJumps\u201d\nto human caretakers and\nfriends, which is very fortu\nnate for all concerned.\nAs for diet, the Persian cat\ndemands no more or differ\nent food than the ordinary\ncat. Raw meat and fish are\nbest, with a little milk, now\nand then, and an occasional\nmeal of manufactured foods,\nif it will eat them.\nPersian cats should be\ncombed at least once a week,\ntwice is better, with care\ntaken to get out the hard\ntangles or \u201cknots.\u201d If these\nare let go unattended, they\nmust be cut off with a scis\nsors.\nQ. Should all moles, any\nwhere on the body, be re\nmoved?\u2014T. H.\nA. There is no need for\nthis. A flat, colorless mole is\nusually as harmless as a\nfreckle. Bluish-black hairless\nmoles, especially when sub\nject to irritation, should be\nremoved. Any wart or mole\nwhich changes size or color\nshould be removed at once,\nand the tissue examined by\na pathologist to determine\nwhether cancer is present","height":"28959","width":"18190"}}
